Average power for cars under normal conditions

source("autopower.R") #take function from R file

# generate sample speeds from a distribution with 10% sd
nsample = 100
speeds = rnorm(mean=28, sd=2.8, n=nsample)

#generate a data frame from the model
results = data.frame(speed=speeds, power=NA)

head(results)
##      speed power
## 1 30.82652    NA
## 2 24.65990    NA
## 3 30.23564    NA
## 4 28.19040    NA
## 5 26.21353    NA
## 6 27.90329    NA
results$power = autopower(V=speeds, A=25, m=20000)

#Use graphs to check
graph_1<- ggplot(results, aes(speed, power/1000))+geom_point()+labs(x="speed in m/s", y="power in kW")
graph_2 <-ggplot(results, aes(x="Across Speed",y=power/1000))+geom_boxplot()+labs(y="power in kW")
graph_1

graph_2

#select mass and area of cars
possible_cars = data.frame(mass=c(31000,45000,38000), area = c(25,30,22))
 

#enter base speed at 100 kmh and convert to m/s
speed_base = 100 * 0.28

#set power equation for three cars selected above
possible_cars$power = autopower(V=speed_base, A = possible_cars$area, m=possible_cars$mass)
 

possible_cars$prob = c(0.4, 0.4, 0.2)

#assume normal distribution and set variable for speed assuming 100 kmh with 10% sd
mn = log(100*0.277)
nsample = 100
speeds = rlnorm(mean=mn, sd=0.1*mn, nsample)
summary(speeds)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   11.65   24.19   29.61   30.67   36.67   59.15
results = data.frame(speed=speeds, power=NA)


#select all possible cars in distribution
possible_cars$row = seq(from=1, to=nrow(possible_cars))
possible_cars
##    mass area    power prob row
## 1 31000   25 226380.0  0.4   1
## 2 45000   30 303760.8  0.4   2
## 3 38000   22 243337.9  0.2   3
whichcar = base::sample(possible_cars$row, size=nsample, prob=possible_cars$prob, replace=TRUE)
whichcar #shows you 100 observations choosing a number between 1 and 3 since three car types are listed
##   [1] 2 3 1 2 1 2 1 1 2 2 1 1 3 1 2 1 1 2 1 2 2 1 2 2 1 1 1 3 3 1 2 2 2 3 2
##  [36] 3 2 1 1 2 3 1 1 3 2 1 2 3 2 2 1 1 2 2 1 2 2 3 2 2 1 3 3 1 3 2 1 1 2 2
##  [71] 3 1 1 2 2 1 3 1 1 1 1 2 2 3 3 2 3 2 2 2 1 2 3 2 2 2 3 1 1 3
#this is basically bootstrapping


head(whichcar)#begining of list of possible car selections
## [1] 2 3 1 2 1 2
#show masses for selected cars in distribution
results$mass = possible_cars$mass[whichcar]

head(results)
##      speed power  mass
## 1 38.24642    NA 45000
## 2 30.43215    NA 38000
## 3 38.96219    NA 31000
## 4 29.04629    NA 45000
## 5 42.37569    NA 31000
## 6 36.58771    NA 45000
# Add areas for selected cars
results$area = possible_cars$area[whichcar]

 

# power for all of our samples of speed and car type

results$power = autopower(A=results$area, V=results$speed, m=results$mass)

summary(results$power)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   60213  208678  295472  349338  445847 1150152
ggplot(results,aes(x="", y=power/1000))+geom_boxplot(fill="red")+labs("Power kW")

Assignment 3:

what if we design new highways that have lower rolling coefficients we can reduce the rolling coefficient by 50% or we can reduce the mean speed to 80 km/h (still with 10% standard deviation) calculate mean power for both (assuming the same car probabilities above) which is better

Based on our analysis, the mean power used over a normal distribution of car weight and surface areas, assuming a speed limit of 100km/h with standard deviation of 10%, rolling coefficient due to friction of 0.15, oefficient due to drag of 0.3, and air pressure of 1.2 kg/m^3 is 3.493382110^{5}w. If we reduce the rolling coefficient/friction of the road by half (to 0.075) the mean power is reduced to 2.915811410^{5}w. Alternatively, if we reduce the speed limit of the road to 80 km/h the mean power is reduced to 2.166137110^{5}w. Lowering the speed limit is less effective at reducing power needed, however this technique would be less expensive to implement.
